# Speevy — Cursor Project Rules

## Product
Speevy ("Speedy SPV") is Harpoon Ventures' internal LP portal for pre-marketing
and managing SPV opportunities. Used by Harpoon admins and invited LPs only.
Not a multi-tenant SaaS. Not publicly marketed. No self-signup.

Harpoon does $100M+/year in deal volume through SPVs. This product is the
presentation layer behind that volume — invest in quality accordingly. But
"quality" means polished, fast, and trustworthy, not flexible-for-the-sake-of-it.

## Users
- **Admins** (Harpoon team): create/edit opportunities, manage LPs, view interest signals
- **LPs** (invited only): verify identity, view opportunities they have access to, indicate interest

## Regulatory Posture
Operating under Reg D 506(b). LPs are invited, no general solicitation.
Accreditation is collected and stored but self-attested unless a deal requires 506(c).
KYC + accreditation handled by Persona or Parallel Markets (TBD — do not lock in
without explicit decision).

## Stack
- Next.js 15, App Router, TypeScript strict mode
- React Server Components by default
- Tailwind CSS + shadcn/ui as the component base
- Supabase: Postgres + Auth + Storage + Row Level Security
- Drizzle ORM — no raw SQL strings in app code (migrations are SQL files)
- Server Actions for mutations, Zod for input validation at every boundary
- Dropbox Sign API for NDAs and subscription documents
- Loops for transactional email and Supabase Auth SMTP
- Tiptap (constrained toolbar) for rich text inside section components
- dnd-kit for section reordering
- Recharts for charts
- PostHog for product analytics (no LP PII in events)
- Vercel for hosting

## Architecture Rules
- **Default to Server Components.** A component becomes a Client Component
  only when it needs state, effects, or browser APIs.
- When a Client Component needs data, pass it as props from a Server Component
  parent. Do not fetch LP or opportunity data from the client.
- All authorization lives in two places: (1) Supabase RLS policies,
  (2) Server Actions / route handlers. Never in React components.
- Every mutation goes through a Server Action with Zod-validated input.
- All file access uses short-lived signed URLs. No public buckets.

## UI Source of Truth
- For every new page or feature, the user will provide the page UI as HTML/CSS
  exported or adapted from Webflow. Treat that HTML/CSS as the visual source of
  truth for the page shell and any elements the user wants to keep custom.
- Go page by page: first implement the provided HTML/CSS as static markup that
  preserves layout, class names, spacing, and styling intent, then hook it up to
  typed data, Server Actions, auth, and RLS-backed access rules.
- Do not invent new page UI from scratch unless the user explicitly asks for it.
- Do not preemptively replace HTML elements with component-library widgets.
  The user will call out specific elements to upgrade — dropdowns, modals,
  sidepanels, tables, etc. — and specify whether to use shadcn/ui or Untitled UI.
- Expect a mixed page model: Webflow HTML/CSS for designed static sections, and
  real Untitled UI/shadcn components only for the specific interactive or data
  elements the user selects for replacement.
- When swapping an element, keep the surrounding page static and make the
  smallest styling adjustments needed so the component matches the page. Do not
  rewrite neighboring Webflow markup just because a component is being replaced.
- shadcn/ui: interactive controls (dropdowns, dialogs, sheets, forms, toasts).
- Untitled UI: admin tables and data-heavy list views.
- When the user links to or asks for an Untitled UI component, use Untitled UI's
  actual React component source via their CLI/manual source. Do not treat
  Untitled UI as design inspiration or recreate the look from scratch.
- Light Speevy styling adjustments are allowed after adding the real Untitled UI
  component, but preserve the component's accessibility and behavior.
- When the user asks to add a table to a page, use Untitled UI's React
  `Alternating fills 01` table example as the default starting point:
  `TableCard.Root`, `TableCard.Header`, `Table`, sortable `Table.Head`
  columns, alternating `odd:bg-secondary` rows, `Badge`/`BadgeWithDot`
  status cells, row action `ButtonUtility` icons, and
  `PaginationPageMinimalCenter`. Add the real Untitled UI component files and
  dependencies first if they are not already present.
- Auth pages: use Untitled UI's `login-split-image` split-view layout as the
  starting point for login and invite acceptance. Speevy has no public signup;
  any "signup" UI is an invite-link flow for an already-invited LP/admin.
- If the provided HTML conflicts with accessibility, responsiveness, or security
  requirements, keep the visual direction and make the smallest practical fix.

## Supabase Client Usage — IMPORTANT
There are two Supabase clients. Use the right one.

- **User-session client** (anon key + user JWT): default for everything.
  RLS does the authorization work. If the policy says no, the query returns
  no rows. Use this for all reads on behalf of an LP or admin.
- **Service role client** (service_role key): bypasses RLS entirely.
  Only allowed in:
  (a) Webhook handlers, AFTER validating the webhook signature
  (b) Audit log inserts (audit_log has no insert policy by design)
  (c) Explicitly admin-only Server Actions where the FIRST LINE validates
      that the caller is an admin via `is_admin()` or equivalent

Never expose the service role through anything an LP can call.
Never put the service role key in a Client Component or in any code that
ships to the browser.

## Opportunity Page Model
Opportunities are composed of **section components**, not arbitrary blocks.
The available section types are a fixed registry. Admins choose which sections
to include and reorder them (dnd-kit). Each section has a structured data
schema (Zod). Rich text inside sections uses Tiptap with a constrained toolbar
(bold, italic, lists, links, pull quote).

Initial section registry (extend deliberately, never casually):
- HeroSection (company name, logo, one-liner, key stats)
- OverviewSection (rich text + optional pull quotes)
- TeamSection (structured: name, role, bio, photo, LinkedIn)
- MarketSection (rich text + optional chart embed)
- TractionSection (metrics grid + chart)
- FinancialsSection (structured numbers + chart)
- TermsSection (round size, valuation, minimum check, Harpoon's allocation)
- MediaSection (image gallery or video embed)
- DocumentsSection (linked files, can be NDA-gated)

Do NOT build a generic block editor. Do NOT allow free-form layout.
Do NOT add new section types without an explicit request.

## Opportunity Statuses
`potential` | `upcoming` | `active` | `past`
LPs can indicate interest on anything except `past`.

## Interest Flow
Two-step: (1) LP indicates interest, (2) LP provides dollar amount.
If opportunity has `minimum_investment_cents`, amount must meet or exceed it.
Interest is one row per LP per opportunity, transitioning through statuses.

## Access Control
- LPs see only opportunities where they have an `opportunity_access` row
  OR the opportunity is flagged `visible_to_all_approved_lps`.
- LPs see opportunity sections (the body) only if they've satisfied the
  NDA gate when `nda_required = true`.
- LPs can see title and teaser of an NDA-gated opportunity before signing
  (so they know what they're being asked to sign for). RLS enforces this
  by gating sections, not the opportunity row itself.
- Enforce all of the above in RLS policies AND in Server Actions.
  Belt and suspenders.

## Money
- All currency stored as `bigint` cents. Never floats. Never integers in dollars.
- Format on display. Parse on input. The DB column is always `*_cents`.

## Security Non-Negotiables
- Every read of an opportunity body by an LP writes an `audit_log` row
  (lp_id, opportunity_id, ip, user_agent, timestamp).
- Every admin write to `lps`, `opportunities`, `opportunity_access`, or
  `interests` writes an `audit_log` row in the same DB transaction.
- No LP PII in logs, PostHog events, or error reports. Scrub before sending.
- All Server Actions validate the caller's role before doing anything.
- Write Vitest tests that simulate LP and admin database connections
  and assert RLS prevents unauthorized reads/writes.
- Per-user dynamic watermark on opportunity pages (LP email + timestamp,
  tiled, low opacity). This is a deterrent and attribution tool, not a
  screenshot prevention mechanism — do not pretend otherwise in code or UI.
- Admin promotion (`profiles.role = 'admin'`) happens ONLY via explicit SQL
  migration. There must be NO application code path that sets role to 'admin'.

## Code Conventions
- TypeScript strict. No `any`. No `as` casts without a comment explaining why.
- Drizzle schema is the source of truth for DB types. Infer, don't duplicate.
- Components live in `components/`. Section components in `components/sections/`.
- Server Actions in `app/**/actions.ts`, colocated with the route that uses them.
- Shared data access in `lib/db/` — all DB queries go through typed functions here.
- Use shadcn/ui primitives. Don't write Tailwind walls — extract components.
- No new top-level dependency without asking first.

## What Not to Build
- No multi-tenancy, no orgs table, no plan tiers, no billing.
- No public signup, no marketing pages, no SEO concerns.
- No white-label abstraction. Harpoon branding is hard-coded.
- No generic block editor. Section registry only.
- No client-side data fetching for LP or opportunity data.
- No "soft delete" flags except where the schema already has them
  (use `archived_at`, `revoked_at`, `withdrawn_at` — not `is_deleted`).

## Build Order
Work in this sequence. Do not start a phase until the previous one is shipped
and tested.
1. Auth + LP invitation + KYC/accreditation flow
2. Admin LP management (table, approve/reject, document upload, audit trail)
3. Opportunity CRUD with section registry (admin side only)
4. LP-facing opportunity list + detail with access control + NDA gate
5. Interest indication flow (two-step, with minimum check)
6. Email notifications + admin interest dashboard
7. Polish, analytics, internal launch

## When in Doubt
Ask before scaffolding. Prefer fewer files, sharper abstractions, and
explicit code over clever code. This is a system that handles real money
and real relationships — boring and correct beats clever and impressive.
